INSERT INTO `wp_postmeta` VALUES("1230", "507", "panels_data", "a:3:{s:7:\"widgets\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"type\";s:6:\"visual\";s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";s:4:\"text\";s:7504:\"<p>Being on a path that is considered outside the societal norm comes with many challenges. Lifestyle choices such as starting a business from home, following a dream to travel and study abroad, pursuing a passion such as art or music; any of these endeavors can often be met with resistance and extreme negativity from the people whose opinions you value the most. While constructive criticism is invaluable to your growth as an individual, regardless of your path, destructive criticism can do much more damage than you may realize. We often ask those we value to tell us what they think. \"Be honest\", we say, and at the time, we probably mean it. While most opinions will be honest but mostly designed to soothe your nervous ego, some of these people will often be less than positive. <br /><br />Learning to recognize a toxic friendship is as difficult a process to initiate as it is painful to remedy. If you discover that someone in your life seems more interested in keeping you down rather than helping you up, the most useful solution may be cutting ties with this influence. Jim Rohn said You are the average of the five people you spend the most time with. If one (or more) of those five never seems to have anything helpful or positive to offer, do you really want to become as they are? You are the master of your own life, and there is no rule that says you must keep every friend you have ever made. If someone always makes you feel worse after spending time with them, there is no law that obligates you to repeatedly torture yourself for their benefit. <br /><br />Once you have identified the people who are less than supportive, the unpleasant task of telling them how you feel will eventually come up. You can consider trying to ignore them, and often times people with this personality will lose interest quickly and move on to their next victim with no need to explain. Sometimes though, this person has been in your life for a long time. Maybe they are a relative, or a friend from school you have always stayed close with over the years and you feel guilty not wanting them around anymore. This is where most people will fall into some level of acceptance with their toxic friendship. The biggest mistake you can make is to become aware of the nature of your relationship and try to ignore it. If you can, be creative with how you approach them. Maybe write a handwritten (but clearly legible!) letter so there is no opportunity for an argument or a copy and paste battle on social media. Maybe record the message in an honest video so they can see your facial expressions and body language and know you are being genuine and straightforward.<br /><br />If they are a true friend, and you do not attack them by telling them you have moved on from their friendship, then you will eventually work out your differences. Maybe they weren\'t aware of your feelings or maybe they weren\'t able to talk to you about some personal issues they were having and they handled it poorly. Who knows what motivates people to be less than good to each other? <br /><br />I have lost almost as many friends as I have acquired over the years and, at first glace, this statement may make me look as if I am an unlikable and unreasonable person. The truth is that I have mastered the art of choosing who I allow within my personal sphere. I can honestly say that out of all the people I have moved on from and left behind, I only miss a couple of them now and again... but then I think of how I always felt after sharing something with them, and I know I made the right decision.<br /><br />So now that you know how to recognize a toxic friendship, how exactly do you let them go? This can be as simple as one attempt or as complex as getting a divorce, but if it is truly over, it is always worth the temporary pain for permanent relief that follows. Letting them down easy seems like a good plan, but being too soft may not get your point across that you are no longer allowing room for their negativity in your life.<br /><br />Here is one example: Hey friend, I have been doing a lot of thinking about the kind of person I am trying to become and how that person fits into the world. I know we have known each other for X-amount of years and you know that I have been trying to work on improving myself in a lot of different ways during that time. We have had some really good times together like, (insert memories) so it is really hard for me to continue, but you need to know how I really feel. When you say things like (give example) or (give example) or (yet another example) when I bring up (things I am excited about) it makes me feel (insert exactly and specifically how you feel with no filter). Maybe you don\'t know you do it, and I would like to believe you wouldn\'t want to hurt me... At this point, I need to be away from our friendship. This may seem sudden to you, but it is what I really need and I hope you can respect that. I hope I made my feelings clear enough for you to understand why this is my final decision and I hope you will be able to move on and find friends who see the world more as you see it. Thanks for the good times... and sign your name.<br /><br />It may seem weird to be this formal, but the tone of the message will immediately be set so there will be less chance that they will feel blindsided when you get to the point. Your objective isn\'t to cause them pain, only to move on so they can\'t cause you any further pain either. I will post an example of how you can use the same basic idea for a video message at the bottom of this blog. When you decide to follow through with cutting ties, you may feel awful for the first few days, even if you haven\'t done it yet. If you are anything like me, however, you will also know that for every good memory with that person there are 10 times they were less than friend material.<br /><br />I hope that no one ever needs to lose a friend. So, therefore I guess no one will have a need for this to begin with, but if you find yourself needing to lose a friend, I hope this will help you do it like a boss.<br /><br />BONUS TIP: If you send this letter or video to your friend and they relentlessly contact you afterward, continue to reply with exactly the same letter or video until they understand that you aren\'t changing your mind about them any time soon. If the situation escalates (in rare instances people go batty), contact the proper authorities and make any mutual friends aware of the situation between the two of you. While I recommend you do the latter either way, the former shouldn\'t be necessary unless the person you are cutting loose has serious issues already. Good luck on your journey to having the friends you deserve.<br /><br />Please subscribe by clicking the \"Subscribe for Updates\" button at the top of this page, or the \"Get Updates\" button at the bottom of this page. I send out messages only when new content is added or has a major update. Thanks for sharing! <br /><br /><br />To sign up for more information on running a successful business and mastering your marketing, click here: <a href=\"http://www.megmillerhilo.com/answers\">www.megmillerhilo.com/answers</a> and sign up for a Free Live training webcast. Once you attend, you will have the opportunity to connect with hundreds of members world-wide, and gain access to all the training you will need to start a business, or to start using these trends in your marketing today. Hope to see you there! <br /><br />- Meg</p>\";s:6:\"filter\";s:1:\"1\";s:11:\"panels_info\";a:5:{s:5:\"class\";s:30:\"WP_Widget_Black_Studio_TinyMCE\";s:4:\"grid\";i:0;s:4:\"cell\";i:0;s:2:\"id\";i:0;s:5:\"style\";a:2:{s:27:\"background_image_attachment\";b:0;s:18:\"background_display\";s:4:\"tile\";}}}}s:5:\"grids\";a:1:{i:0;a:2:{s:5:\"cells\";i:1;s:5:\