INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("42", "3", "2016-09-18 07:15:00", "2016-09-18 07:15:00", "Being bold used to be a breeze for me. Back in middle school, if I even thought I might know the answer, I was always the first one with my hand up. As I grew into adulthood, however, something changed. I found myself feeling less confident or even embarrassed for being the center of attention. Eventually, I got to the point that I would sit in the back of the class, keep my head down, and try not to be seen. My entire childhood had been fueled by not being afraid to speak up, to be noticed, to be remarkable. And you know what, life was a heck of a lot more fun back then.\n<h3>So what made me start feeling insecure?</h3>\nGrowing up means a lot of different things, especially in these accelerated times. As I learned and grew (and especially once I got to college) being bold no longer felt like a good thing. I would often stop myself from fully participating in both academic and social activities, because, I wasnt sure what people would think of me. Sound familiar?\n\nIn fact, even the things I did do were always done based on the expected reaction of others. At some point, I basically stopped doing anything for myself, and started basing the whole of my experience on doing and saying what I felt others would best respond to. And it wasnt at all fulfilling.\n\nI ended up graduating with a degree I didnt care about, working in a job I disliked, and trying really hard to just forget about it all on the weekends. My attachment to the opinions of others created a negative spiral that kept chipping away at my self worth until one day, I had had enough\n<h3>So I moved toHawaii</h3>\nAt this point, you may be saying Huh? But honestly this is the one thing I did that started to rebuild my confidence and make me feel the joy of life again. Im not saying you have to move to Hawaii (or at all) but the point here is that to break the cycle of self fulfilling dullness, <strong><em>you must take action!</em></strong> Pick something, do it, and really live that experience. For me, I needed the shift in location because many of my barriers were based on living in the same place I grew up and doing many of the same hobbies, activities, and jobs I had always done.\n\nThrough my taking action to plan (if you can call what I had a plan) a backpacking trip to the rain forests of Hawaii by myself (despite what my friends, parents, and pretty much everyone I knew thought about that plan) I set into motion a series of events that have cascaded into an incredibly richer and freer life. I met my gorgeous fiancee Meg, traveled to unique and amazing places (often with little planning and too much to carry), and become a much bolder and empowered person.\n<h3>Fortune Favors theBold</h3>\nHave you ever heard that saying, Fortune favors the bold? This has become one of my favorite quotes of all time because it truly illustrates that to live a great life, you have to do great things. And great things usually come in <strong class=\"markup--strong markup--p-strong\">bold</strong> packages. If you want to make a better loaf of bread, use better ingredients, right?\n\nAll of the most successful, fulfilled, and awesome people I know live every day according to what they desire to accomplish. They dont worry that one of their friends might think they are weird or that they will have to be outside their comfort zone. True happiness comes from living your bliss and sharing it with others!\n\nSo if youre ready to stop watching your life from the sidelines, do this today:\n<ol>\n 	<li>Think of something youhave always wanted to do or experience in your life. (Dont think of what others will think, only <strong><em>what you want to do</em></strong>)</li>\n 	<li>Close your eyes and imagine yourself doing it. Be specific! Where are you? Who else is there? What are you wearing? etc.</li>\n 	<li>Experience that feeling as deeply as you can. Now hold onto that feeling and open your eyes.</li>\n 	<li>Ask yourself, How can I make that experience happen? What would it take to get you there?</li>\n 	<li>Take action! Do at least one thing today to get started on the path toward that experience. Call your old friend who lives in Costa Rica, sell that old exercise bike you never use, call or email someone who is already doing what you want to do and ask them how they got there, just do something!</li>\n</ol>\nThe key to all of this is follow through. Start approaching experiences you desire through the lens of what can I do today to rather than I cant do that until Once you start taking actions to achieve your goals, they will start to build and accelerate. Eventually, you will find yourself in what is sometimes called the flow state where life seeming provides you with all the opportunities you could ask for to do the things you want. (This is not actually true, you have provided these for yourself, but the effortlessness with which you will be able to live your truth will make it seem like it is given to you).\n\nIf you were here to be safe, youd be a turtle. Youre here to be bold so go out and do something great! I truly believe every person has something amazing to share with the world, but only if they can conquer their fear. Living according to the expectations of others will almost never lead to fulfilling your expectations of yourself.\n\nReply to this post and let me know if youve had a similar experience shrinking your lifestyle to meet the expectations of others. Or just let me know what you want to do or experience (and what your first step is to achieving it)!", "Go for the BoldHow to transform fear into excitement and live a happier life", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "go-for-the-bold%e2%80%8a-%e2%80%8ahow-to-transform-fear-into-excitement-and-live-a-happier-life", "", "", "2016-09-18 07:15:00", "2016-09-18 07:15:00", "", "0", "http://makeyourliving.info/?p=42", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("507", "2", "2016-03-21 06:44:08", "2016-03-21 06:44:08", "Being on a path that is considered outside the societal norm comes with many challenges. Lifestyle choices such as starting a business from home, following a dream to travel and study abroad, pursuing a passion such as art or music; any of these endeavors can often be met with resistance and extreme negativity from the people whose opinions you value the most. While constructive criticism is invaluable to your growth as an individual, regardless of your path, destructive criticism can do much more damage than you may realize. We often ask those we value to tell us what they think. \"Be honest\", we say, and at the time, we probably mean it. While most opinions will be honest but mostly designed to soothe your nervous ego, some of these people will often be less than positive.\n\nLearning to recognize a toxic friendship is as difficult a process to initiate as it is painful to remedy. If you discover that someone in your life seems more interested in keeping you down rather than helping you up, the most useful solution may be cutting ties with this influence. Jim Rohn said You are the average of the five people you spend the most time with. If one (or more) of those five never seems to have anything helpful or positive to offer, do you really want to become as they are? You are the master of your own life, and there is no rule that says you must keep every friend you have ever made. If someone always makes you feel worse after spending time with them, there is no law that obligates you to repeatedly torture yourself for their benefit.\n\nOnce you have identified the people who are less than supportive, the unpleasant task of telling them how you feel will eventually come up. You can consider trying to ignore them, and often times people with this personality will lose interest quickly and move on to their next victim with no need to explain. Sometimes though, this person has been in your life for a long time. Maybe they are a relative, or a friend from school you have always stayed close with over the years and you feel guilty not wanting them around anymore. This is where most people will fall into some level of acceptance with their toxic friendship. The biggest mistake you can make is to become aware of the nature of your relationship and try to ignore it. If you can, be creative with how you approach them. Maybe write a handwritten (but clearly legible!) letter so there is no opportunity for an argument or a copy and paste battle on social media. Maybe record the message in an honest video so they can see your facial expressions and body language and know you are being genuine and straightforward.\n\nIf they are a true friend, and you do not attack them by telling them you have moved on from their friendship, then you will eventually work out your differences. Maybe they weren\'t aware of your feelings or maybe they weren\'t able to talk to you about some personal issues they were having and they handled it poorly. Who knows what motivates people to be less than good to each other?\n\nI have lost almost as many friends as I have acquired over the years and, at first glace, this statement may make me look as if I am an unlikable and unreasonable person. The truth is that I have mastered the art of choosing who I allow within my personal sphere. I can honestly say that out of all the people I have moved on from and left behind, I only miss a couple of them now and again... but then I think of how I always felt after sharing something with them, and I know I made the right decision.\n\nSo now that you know how to recognize a toxic friendship, how exactly do you let them go? This can be as simple as one attempt or as complex as getting a divorce, but if it is truly over, it is always worth the temporary pain for permanent relief that follows. Letting them down easy seems like a good plan, but being too soft may not get your point across that you are no longer allowing room for their negativity in your life.\n\nHere is one example: Hey friend, I have been doing a lot of thinking about the kind of person I am trying to become and how that person fits into the world. I know we have known each other for X-amount of years and you know that I have been trying to work on improving myself in a lot of different ways during that time. We have had some really good times together like, (insert memories) so it is really hard for me to continue, but you need to know how I really feel. When you say things like (give example) or (give example) or (yet another example) when I bring up (things I am excited about) it makes me feel (insert exactly and specifically how you feel with no filter). Maybe you don\'t know you do it, and I would like to believe you wouldn\'t want to hurt me... At this point, I need to be away from our friendship. This may seem sudden to you, but it is what I really need and I hope you can respect that. I hope I made my feelings clear enough for you to understand why this is my final decision and I hope you will be able to move on and find friends who see the world more as you see it. Thanks for the good times... and sign your name.\n\nIt may seem weird to be this formal, but the tone of the message will immediately be set so there will be less chance that they will feel blindsided when you get to the point. Your objective isn\'t to cause them pain, only to move on so they can\'t cause you any further pain either. I will post an example of how you can use the same basic idea for a video message at the bottom of this blog. When you decide to follow through with cutting ties, you may feel awful for the first few days, even if you haven\'t done it yet. If you are anything like me, however, you will also know that for every good memory with that person there are 10 times they were less than friend material.\n\nI hope that no one ever needs to lose a friend. So, therefore I guess no one will have a need for this to begin with, but if you find yourself needing to lose a friend, I hope this will help you do it like a boss.\n\nBONUS TIP: If you send this letter or video to your friend and they relentlessly contact you afterward, continue to reply with exactly the same letter or video until they understand that you aren\'t changing your mind about them any time soon. If the situation escalates (in rare instances people go batty), contact the proper authorities and make any mutual friends aware of the situation between the two of you. While I recommend you do the latter either way, the former shouldn\'t be necessary unless the person you are cutting loose has serious issues already. Good luck on your journey to having the friends you deserve!\n\n-- Meg", "How to Lose Friends Like a Boss", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "how-to-lose-friends-like-a-boss", "", "", "2016-03-21 06:44:08", "2016-03-21 06:44:08", "", "0", "http://megmillerhilo.com/?p=507", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("510", "2", "2016-04-17 06:48:31", "2016-04-17 06:48:31", "If you run a business, or hope to someday soon, I would like to pass along some tips that I have learned over and over during my experience as an owner. I would like to share the benefit of my efforts so you can avoid the same pitfalls when operating or setting up your own business.\n\nThere is an underlying concept in any endeavor that can basically summed up as this: Everything costs something. There will be some kind of price to pay, whether it is \"financial cost\" or a greater cost such as \"time cost\" reserved for your family or for yourself. Knowing when to learn new skills to move forward in your business, and maybe more importantly, learning when to outsource to a professional will save you costs in all forms. Here are some things to consider when you need to know if it\'s a job for your own skillset or for your pocketbook. I will include examples to give you a basic idea of how you can relate each question to your own business situation.\n\n1. How urgent is this learning this new skill?\nIf you are going to need to know how to build a webpage from scratch in two weeks, but you are a beginner, this is probably not going to be the best time to use your \"time cost\" to complete this project.\n2. How much do you already know about this new skill?\nIf you are a beginner level and you really need an advanced level completed project, check your timeframe from above and decide if it\'s worth learning.\n3. How often will I use this new skill in the future?\nIf you are constantly needing to outsource simple tasks like updating your busines blog, or you are spending a fortune on a marketing agency, maybe you could consider learning the skill to save time and money later.\n4. Could you learn this new skill over an extended period and slowly  implement the skill into your business?\nIf there is a skill you could learn by taking a course or training with a group, but it takes several months or years to complete, ask yourself some of the other questions and see if you could benefit from learning this skill yourself.\n5. Is the \"time cost\" worth your investment, or would \"financial cost\" be better?\nAnother way to word this question is: if the \"time cost\" requires you to be away from your family, or to sacrifice your personal time, will the investment be worth it to you? Sometimes the \"time cost\" is not convienent and would require a larger sacrifice than the \"financial cost\" would be in the end. Consider this carefully.\n6. Would you enjoy learning and implementing this new skill?\nIf you are particularly excited to learn how to advertise on Facebook because the idea of getting paid on social media amazes you, then learn it! Anything you would find enjoyable and is still an asset to your business skill set is a winner!\n7. If you find the right level of \"financial cost\", i.e. price, will the quality be the same as if you learned the skill yourself?\nIf you have a very specific need or preference in mind for your outsourcing project, you may pay additional costs for services to personalize your service. Keep this in mind when you consider learning your new skill... you can always customize!\n8. Is there someone in your business network that could offer assistance, training, or even a discount on the product or service your skill would fill?\nIf you can use your network for expanding your skill set, personal or extended, then you will always have great options as well as some reliable advice on what to learn and what to hire out.\n9. Regardless of any of the other questions above, this is the most important question to ask yourself before learning a new skill, or outsourcing... Ready...?\n\nAre you capable of learning this new skill at all?\nI have always wanted to learn to play the guitar, but I don\'t seem capable of the level of commitment and bloody fingers it takes to really become proficient. I had to eventually decide that I may not be capable of learning the guitar at all. While this may not be totally true, it\'s true enough for now and I have abandoned my quest for more logical passions.\n\nI wish I would have had this list of questions handy a few times when starting my online business. I would have saved myself countless hours in \"time cost\" and countless dollars in \"financial cost\" if I had only taken the time to really consider these aspects. Ultimately, anything you learn is probably going to benefit your business in one way or another, it\'s just a matter of whether you see the actual return on your investment or just add another skill to your repetoir...\n\nInvesting in \"time cost\" can be incredibly powerful when used wisely. If you and your loved ones agree that for x amount of time, we will all sacrifice the \"time cost\" of learning this skill, you can accomplish great things and gain extra time with your family and friends in the long run. Sometimes the bottom line is too complicated to sort out using a generic list of questions. Only you truly know what\'s best for you and your business, so follow your instincts! As long as you learn something, you will get a return on your investment, however small it may be!\n\nTo sign up for more information on running a successful business and mastering your marketing, click here to get the<a href=\"http://www.megmillerhilo.com/answers\" target=\"_blank\">ANSWERS</a>start your journey with a Free Online Workshop. Once you attend, you will have the opportunity to connect with hundreds of members world-wide, and gain access to all the training you will need to start a business, or to start using these trends in your marketing today. Looking forward to seeing you there!\n\n- Meg", "When to Substitute Time for Money (and when not to...)", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "when-to-substitute-time-for-money-and-when-not-to", "", "", "2016-04-17 06:48:31", "2016-04-17 06:48:31", "", "0", "http://megmillerhilo.com/?p=510", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("513", "2", "2016-04-21 07:04:35", "2016-04-21 07:04:35", "We live in a visual world. Videos rule and text is mostly for the few times we can\'t turn up our volume. Instagram, Flickr, Twitter, Facebook, Youtube... the list goes on and on. The wave of the future is definitely already here and that future is Visual Advertising.\n\nThis is a great opportunity, and also a two-sided coin, which you can utilize to further your marketing efforts. If you learn some new skills and become familiar with the basic apps and programs, you can get your brand out to the world for next to zero investment, without having to \"sell\" yourself.\n\nSide one of the coin is obvious. By using videos and pictures to educate your prospect about your products or services, you are using the most current and effective trend for marketing today. If you notice, Facebook is full of video advertisements, and many of them lead to a video training which is either a live webcast event or a video training series to be completed over time. This is a mega-trend and you would be wise to jump on this bandwagon before it\'s yesterday\'s news! You have a tremendous opportunity to use video to tell the story of your brand. Show the prospect how they will realistically benefit from having what you offer. The days of the carefully constructed studio commercial are quickly fading because people are waking up and seeing through the blatant advertising. People love to buy things but no one likes to be \"sold\" something... Think on that for a moment.\n\nThe other side of the coin may not be so obvious. However, if you understand the second aspect to following this mega-trend, you will understand the true power of the internet for getting your brand recognized. Before I tell you what exactly it is, because it is very simple but difficult to summarize, I will lead with a generic example that maybe you can relate to your situation...\n\nI work from home doing various virtual assistant gigs and a little web developing. My passion is running my business where I offer some amazing products and services. I found myself struggling with some outdated technology, so I decided to upgrade to a new computer. It was a huge risk and investment, but I knew it would give me time back in my life that I would previously have spent dealing with technical issues. Since I got my new system, I now have several extra hours in my life to do more of the things I enjoy doing! Not to mention the fact that I often get paid a flat rate, so getting done sooner almost doubles my income. I am so happy I made the decision to move forward with getting a new computer.\n\nThis is a true example, it\'s a small bit of my story... but chances are, you either aren\'t reading anymore (because you see the video underneath this block of text already!!) or you are anxious to get to the video so you are skimming quickly. I want you to notice two things right now. (Even if you are reading this part AFTER you watched the video). One: You are more attracted to a person\'s face rather than a block of letters on a plain background. Two: Think back to the example above... Were you thinking of a piece of equipment, software, service, etc. that you have been wanting for your business while I was talking about my computer? Did you think about needing a new computer? I was telling you about my wonderful experience and what turned out to be a great business decision. At no point did I try to sell you anything. But didn\'t you feel like buying something to gain more time and money in your life by the time I finished the story?[spacer height=\"20px\"]\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/UWorMzATVDE\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]</p>\nThe second side of the coin is important because it puts you on the same level of your prospect. If you are really excited and genuinely ready to show them something of value, they are more likely to trust you, and they are more likely to like you. If they like you, they will purchase from you. Bottom line. If you treat your advertising like you would treat a letter to a friend about the wonderful things happening in your life (like the computer example above) then you will undoubtedly be successful following today\'s \"show me a story\" trend in marketing.\n\nTo sign up for more information on running a successful business and mastering your marketing, click here to get the<a href=\"http://www.megmillerhilo.com/answers\" target=\"_blank\">ANSWERS</a>start your journey with a Free Online Workshop. Once you attend, you will have the opportunity to connect with hundreds of members world-wide, and gain access to all the training you will need to start a business, or to start using these trends in your marketing today. Looking forward to seeing you there!\n\n- Meg", "Don\'t Sell, Show and Tell Instead", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "dont-sell-show-and-tell-instead", "", "", "2016-04-21 07:04:35", "2016-04-21 07:04:35", "", "0", "http://megmillerhilo.com/?p=513", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("522", "3", "2016-04-21 07:33:24", "2016-04-21 07:33:24", "Rewind about 6 months and my life would now seem unrecognizable. I was feeling tired, broke and listless. I had no motivation and felt like my life was stuck in an endless cycle of work, sleep, and paying bills. Since I cook for a living, I would often end up eating leftovers every night. Then one day, I came home from work to find my fiancee full of excitement about a new opportunity she had discovered. At the time, my conditioned response would have been skepticism and doubt. Her excitement was strong, however, and I couldn\'t help but catch on to it. So I sat down and looked at the opportunity and, in a moment of boldness uncharacteristic for me at the time, decided to take action. My life changed forever that night.\n\nWhat happened to me is called a paradigm shift. Basically I experienced a change in perspective that allowed me to see my situation in a different light. I suddenly began realizing that the reason I felt like I was stuck in my life was because I wasn\'t changing my actions to get different results. I had been blind to the fact that as long as I kept simply going to work for my paycheck and stressing out about it so much that I had no time to pursue, or even think about what my dreams were or how to achieve them. I was stuck in a rut, but it wasn\'t due to my circumstances, it was because I kept doing the same thing every day.\n\nMy fiancee and I have seen our lives accelerate in a way neither of us would have thought possible previously. I still have the same job, the same car, and the same apartment, yet we are happier, more motivated and more fulfilled in all aspects of life because of our paradigm shift. By consciously choosing to admit our responsibility for our situation, shift our perspective, and take action, we have been able to attract a much more abundant life. Simply by focusing on how we desired our lives to be, rather than how hard things were, our desires began to appear all around us. We began to have extra money at the end of each paycheck, even enough to invest a little. The financing for our business came through. I got a big raise at work and Meg got a job working from home. Now if we want to grab some takeout so we don\'t have to cook every night, we don\'t even worry if we can afford it. We know we can.\n\nSo there you have it. With a simple change in perspective, we have been able to shift into high gear and accelerate our lives. If you are feeling bad about the way things are going, try changing your paradigm and see yourself at your best. See yourself as the victorious you that we all know you are and you will become it.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<center><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/w9HQFNe85yA\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></center><center></center>&nbsp;", "Paradigm Shift Yourself into High Gear", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "paradigm-shift-yourself-into-high-gear", "", "", "2016-04-21 07:33:24", "2016-04-21 07:33:24", "", "0", "http://megmillerhilo.com/?p=522", "0", "post", "", "0");
